## 2. Environmental and Socioeconomic Impacts

### 2.1 Sea-Level Rise and Housing Security

Global sea levels have risen approximately 7-8 inches since 1900, with 3 inches since 1993, threatening coastal communities through inundation and increased flooding. This phenomenon leads to displacement and “climate gentrification,” where lower-income residents are displaced by wealthier populations moving inland ([Climate Reality, 2019](https://www.climaterealityproject.org/blog/how-climate-change-affecting-our-lives)).

### 2.2 Food Security and Nutrition

Elevated CO2 levels alter plant physiology, increasing sugar content but reducing essential nutrients such as calcium, protein, zinc, and vitamins in fruits and vegetables. By mid-century, this could result in 175 million additional people with zinc deficiency and 122 million with protein deficiency globally ([Climate Reality, 2019](https://www.climaterealityproject.org/blog/how-climate-change-affecting-our-lives)).

### 2.3 Economic Vulnerability and Poverty

Climate change exacerbates poverty by increasing health-related expenditures and pushing approximately 100 million people into poverty annually due to health shocks. Poor populations, often uninsured, face compounded barriers to accessing healthcare, threatening progress toward universal health coverage ([World Health Organization, 2022](https://internationalgbc.org/)).

---

## 3. Climate Change and Human Mobility

### 3.1 Migration, Displacement, and Planned Relocation

Climate change influences human movement through sudden-onset disasters (storms, floods) and slow-onset phenomena (drought, sea-level rise). Movements include displacement (forced), migration (voluntary), and planned relocation (state-led resettlement). Most movements occur within countries, but cross-border migration is increasing, especially from vulnerable regions ([Weerasinghe, 2021](https://cmsny.org/what-we-know-about-climate-change-and-migration-final/)).

### 3.2 Vulnerable and Trapped Populations

Some populations are "trapped" due to lack of resources or legal barriers, unable to move away from hazardous areas. Others choose to remain despite risks. Effective policies must address these diverse circumstances, ensuring protection and support ([Weerasinghe, 2021](https://cmsny.org/what-we-know-about-climate-change-and-migration-final/)).

### 3.3 Policy and Legal Frameworks

International frameworks such as the Nansen Initiative Protection Agenda and the Global Compact for Migration recognize the need to address climate-related mobility, though gaps remain in legal protections for climate migrants. Human rights law offers limited but evolving avenues for protection ([Weerasinghe, 2021](https://cmsny.org/what-we-know-about-climate-change-and-migration-final/)).

---

## 4. Trends in Vulnerability and Adaptation

### 4.1 Declining Vulnerability Despite Rising Hazards

Empirical evidence shows a significant decline in human and economic vulnerability to climate-related hazards over recent decades. From 1980–1989 to 2007–2016, mortality rates dropped more than sixfold and economic loss rates nearly fivefold globally. This decline is attributed to improved disaster risk management, early warning systems, and infrastructure ([Formetta & Feyen, 2019](https://doi.org/10.1016/j.gloenvcha.2019.05.004)).

### 4.2 Persistent Inequalities

Despite overall improvements, low- and middle-income countries remain disproportionately vulnerable, with mortality rates 4.4 times higher and economic loss rates nearly four times higher than in wealthier countries. Vulnerability gaps are especially pronounced for coastal floods and wind-related hazards ([Formetta & Feyen, 2019](https://doi.org/10.1016/j.gloenvcha.2019.05.004)).

### 4.3 Wealth as a Protective Factor

There is a clear negative correlation between wealth (GDP per capita) and vulnerability to climate hazards. Investments in protection measures, health infrastructure, and social safety nets reduce mortality and economic losses ([Formetta & Feyen, 2019](https://doi.org/10.1016/j.gloenvcha.2019.05.004)).

---

## 5. Case Study: Australia’s Climate and Health Challenges

Australia exemplifies the multifaceted impacts of climate change, including extreme weather events, disease spread, food and water insecurity, job disruptions, and social security threats. Vulnerable groups include the sick, elderly, young, poor, pregnant women, and socially isolated individuals. Recommendations emphasize identifying vulnerable populations, coordinated research, improved communication, and emission reductions ([Australian Academy of Science, 2015](https://www.science.org.au/files/userfiles/support/reports-and-plans/2015/climate-change-challenges-health.pdf)).

---

## 6. Opportunities and Co-Benefits

Mitigation strategies that reduce greenhouse gas emissions can yield immediate health benefits, such as improved air quality and increased physical activity through better urban planning. Transitioning to clean energy and sustainable food systems can simultaneously address climate change and public health ([Haines, 2021](https://www.sei.org/events/climate-change-and-health-developing-evidence-for-action/)).

